{"author":{"id":"a56ba7ab6d78f09a5b420e03d7dcf8909af63d2d7cf7996811a8ac1c9bd1f114"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1491312301,"nonce":"34cm4rHQNnrJE9zCIQHtciWplPk=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUyMTkyNDk0MzM=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1230","origin":"github"},"title":"Important but not \"best practice\" tools?","message":"I think many of us have written tools that are useful and maybe even important but didn't quite rise to the level of \"best practice\" - and the bar for \"best practice\" is ever rising. Much of the time the limitation isn't even a lack of effort on the part of the tool author - it could be problems with the underlying application itself or limitations due to data handling in Galaxy or the tool test framework or licensing restrictions.  I think community support of such tools may still be important though.\n\nWhat should be the IUC policy for such tools?\n - Should they not be added to this repository or should they?\n - If yes, should they be put in a separate directory - like an incubator or something?\n - If no, should a separate repository and tool shed org be created? Should devteam be used? Should we not have a community effort for such tools because this repository already has so many open PRs for the existing tools?\n\nMy own thoughts are that it is really valuable to have only high quality, tested tools in this repository - it means we can easily point new developers at this repository and be confident all the tools are well written and good examples and it means deployers are super confident when installing anything from IUC. I would lean toward a new repository and a new tool shed organization - but I luckily don't get a vote.","files":null}]}